{"name":"National Issues - India","id":185,"content":"<h2>Overview</h2>\n\n<p><strong>Individual Aspect</strong>: Food, Health, Education, Shelter/ House, Employment</p>\n\n<p><strong>Planet Earth Aspect</strong>: Climate Change, Global Warming, Natural Resources Depletion, Overpopulation, Pollution, Loss of Biodiversity/ Habitat.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Societal Aspect</strong>: Communal Riots, Religious Riots, Terrorism, Gender Discrimination, Inequality, Crime, Racism/ Castism.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Administrative/ Infrastructural Aspect</strong>: Corruption, Lack of dedication, Coercion.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2>Foor, Hunger, Malnutrition</h2>\n\n<p><u>Good News</u>:&nbsp;The economy is among the top 10 percentile of fastest growing, and over the past 60 years, life expectancy nearly doubled and adult literacy more than quadrupled.&nbsp;Between 2005 and 2010, 53 million people were lifted out of poverty.</p>\n\n<p><strong><u>Bad News</u></strong>: There are a lot of people in India suffering from lack of food, malnutrition (Refer to <a href=\"http://www.fao.org/publications/card/en/c/CA1796EN\" target=\"_blank\">UN Report</a>). In&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/india_statistics.html\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">2010</a>, 69% still lived on less than the US $2 a day, and 33% on less than the US $1.25 a day. (Reference: <a href=\"http://www.thp.org/our-work/where-we-work/india/\" target=\"_blank\">TheHungerProject</a>)</p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\">&nbsp;Over 20 crore people will sleep hungry tonight. (Reference:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.bhookh.com/hunger_facts.php\">Bhookh.com</a>&nbsp;accessed on 18th Nov&nbsp;2018)</div>\n\n<p>India&#39;s health situation <a href=\"http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/136895/ccsbrief_ind_en.pdf?sequence=1\" target=\"_blank\">WHO Report</a>.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Summary: India has made a great progress, but a huge number of still affected by health problems. There is a huge inequality among the states regarding health situations (in some places it&#39;s very bad&nbsp;For example, MMR in Kerala was 61 compared to 300 in Assam (2013), and girls in India have a higher prevalence of undernourishment than boys).</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/136895/ccsbrief_ind_en.pdf?sequence=1\" target=\"_blank\">WHO Detailed Report</a></p>\n\n<p>Government expenditure on health is around 1% of GDP. This has resulted in:</p>\n\n<p>i. Inadequate financial protection in health and high out of pocket (OOP) - more than 62% of spending on health by Indians represents OOP and around 60 million people are pushed into poverty due to OOP.<br />\nii. Relative low health outcomes with a high burden of communicable diseases, including neglected tropical diseases, TB and a high risk of premature death due to NCDs.<br />\niii. Weak public health system and sub-optimal capacities in surveillance and infection control.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","authorId":null,"subject":"stats","tags":["basic","intro"],"img":null,"summary":null,"lastUpdated":"2018-07-02T17:06:50.734+0000"}